comments.body:
I saw this one and I agree we should enable DNS by default for Walrus as EC2 AMI Tools no longer use path style naming by default. Infact they also do not provide a way to enable path style bucket naming from the tool unless you *hack* the EC2 AMI Tools 

Following file was modified inside the ec2-ami-tools: 

lib/ec2/common/s3support.rb

Original

{code}
def initialize(s3_url, user, pass, format=nil, debug=nil)
        @user = user
        @pass = pass
        @s3_url = fix_s3_url(s3_url)
        @format = format || :subdomain
        @debug = debug
      end
{code}

Modified

{code}
def initialize(s3_url, user, pass, format=nil, debug=nil)
        @user = user
        @pass = pass
        @s3_url = fix_s3_url(s3_url)
        @format = format || :path
        @debug = debug
      end
{code}

Then run the ec2-upload-bundle and it should work.

Note again: Its a *hack* not a clean way of doing it.

Here's a somewhat less hackish way to do this that only requires us to make walrus accept additional Host headers.  {{myregion}}, {{mycloud.example.com}}, and {{bukkit}} are placeholders in this (admittedly untested) example:

Add an authoritative zone called {{s3-myregion.amazonaws.com.}} to one's DNS resolver that contains the following record:

{code}
s3-myregion.amazonaws.com.  IN  DNAME  walrus.mycloud.example.com.
{code}

DNS lookups for a bucket called {{bukkit}} would then proceed as follows:
{code}
s3-myregion.amazonaws.com.          3600  IN  DNAME  walrus.mycloud.example.com.
bucket.s3-myregion.amazonaws.com.   0     IN  CNAME  bukkit.walrus.mycloud.example.com.
bukkit.walrus.mycloud.example.com.  20    IN  A      192.0.2.1
{code}
